<node CREATED="1444524962081" ID="ID_155643164" MODIFIED="1444524969323" TEXT="Tuples vs Lists">
<node CREATED="1444524969752" ID="ID_508514641" MODIFIED="1444525011014" TEXT="Why not just use lists instead of tuples everwhere?">
<node CREATED="1444525011964" ID="ID_1453906421" MODIFIED="1444525022105" TEXT="Tuples use less space."/>
<node CREATED="1444525022334" ID="ID_1629238153" MODIFIED="1444525044749" TEXT="You can&apos;t clobber tuple items by mistake."/>
<node CREATED="1444525047372" ID="ID_338487180" MODIFIED="1444525068295" TEXT="You can use tuples as dictionary keys."/>
<node CREATED="1444525068918" ID="ID_247866290" MODIFIED="1444525090280" TEXT="Named tuples can be a simple alternative to objects."/>
<node CREATED="1444525090831" ID="ID_964502862" MODIFIED="1444525112122" TEXT="Function arguments are passed as tuples."/>
</node>
</node>
</node>
<node CREATED="1444525201107" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_1472834377" MODIFIED="1445798555730" TEXT="Dictionaries">
<node CREATED="1444525277158" ID="ID_735630999" MODIFIED="1444526193494">
<richcontent TYPE="NODE"><html>
  <head>
    
  </head>
  <body>
    <p>
      A dictionary is similar to a list, but the order of item doesn't matter, and they aren't select by an offset such as 0 or 1.
    </p>
    <p>
      Instead, you specify a unique key to associate with each value.
    </p>
    <p>
      The key must be unique.
    </p>
  </body>
</html></richcontent>
</node>
